The length of copyright and the kinds of enforcement
in a civil and now

00:43:53.720 --> 00:43:57.751
criminal penalties for copyright infringement
have become more

00:43:57.751 --> 00:44:01.859
stringent, even as the cost of creation, distribution
has gone down.

00:44:01.859 --> 00:44:03.819
Of course, the cost of privacy has also gone
down.

00:44:03.819 --> 00:44:07.339
But that is the only thing so far that the
law responds to.

00:44:07.339 --> 00:44:12.979
It doesn't respond to these other features.
And the analogy I use to talk about copyrights

00:44:12.979 --> 00:44:17.079
is essentially, it's as
if every time cars got faster, we lowered

00:44:17.079 --> 00:44:19.670
the speed limit on the
freeway in response.

00:44:19.670 --> 00:44:22.359
You know, because we want to make sure there
are fewer accidents, so

00:44:22.359 --> 00:44:26.269
that's certainly one goal.
The problem is as we've done that, the cars

00:44:26.269 --> 00:44:28.960
get faster and the speed
limit goes down and basically we now have

00:44:28.960 --> 00:44:32.739
a freeway where the speed
limit is one mile an hour.

00:44:32.739 --> 00:44:36.520
What happens when you have a law that's completely
unrealistic to

00:44:36.520 --> 00:44:40.319
reality is nobody obeys it.
So effectively, we have a copyright system

00:44:40.319 --> 00:44:44.390
and, you know, for all
intents and purposes, it has no basis -- no

00:44:44.390 --> 00:44:46.359
value in terms of how
people behave.

00:44:46.359 --> 00:44:48.569
It doesn't effect their decision to do one
thing or another thing.

00:44:48.569 --> 00:44:53.329
You know, you can pick off individuals every
now and then through

00:44:53.329 --> 00:44:56.109
litigation.
The bottom line is that the system is now

00:44:56.109 --> 00:44:57.700
without a governing body of
law.

00:44:57.700 --> 00:45:01.460
It's kind of, you know, the market is setting
certain rules and certain

00:45:01.460 --> 00:45:06.569
terms.
And again, every now and then there's a piece

00:45:06.569 --> 00:45:08.249
of litigation for --
obviously, the Google/Viacom case still pending

00:45:08.249 --> 00:45:14.859
is an attempt to try
and enforce the one mile an hour speed limit

00:45:14.859 --> 00:45:15.859
on a 55-mile an hour
vehicle.

00:45:15.859 --> 00:45:20.150
Ultimately, those things may have some influence.
But really what's determining the law of copyright

00:45:20.150 --> 00:45:22.849
today -- or the use
of information has nothing to do with the

00:45:22.849 --> 00:45:28.239
copyright law it has
everything to do with the market forces.

00:45:28.239 --> 00:45:32.280
And just to, sort of, close it up, in, you
know, in my copyright

00:45:32.280 --> 00:45:36.849
chapter I sort of said, well, here's three
what I think of as modest

00:45:36.849 --> 00:45:39.380
reforms.
Again, kind of in the Brooks Adams model of

00:45:39.380 --> 00:45:42.579
things what we actually
do -- by the way, there's absolutely no chance

00:45:42.579 --> 00:45:47.450
any of these things
would happen in Congress today, anyway.

00:45:47.450 --> 00:45:50.420
But not because nobody thinks there're a good
idea just because the

00:45:50.420 --> 00:45:55.349
political will wouldn't be there.
But in fact, if we wanted to actually turn

00:45:55.349 --> 00:45:58.299
the copyright system into
something that worked in the digital economy,

00:45:58.299 --> 00:46:01.779
I think, you know, sort
of three things that would have a great deal

00:46:01.779 --> 00:46:05.979
of help.
There one would be dial back on the extension

00:46:05.979 --> 00:46:09.489
of copyright, to put it
back to a reasonable term, reasonable enforcement,

00:46:09.489 --> 00:46:10.800
reasonable
penalties.

00:46:10.800 --> 00:46:15.369
People will maybe obey a law that they think
makes a certain amount of

00:46:15.369 --> 00:46:18.839
sense.
Restoring the concept of fair use, of uses

00:46:18.839 --> 00:46:21.990
that don't have to be
licensed.

00:46:21.990 --> 00:46:25.180
Licensing can be very expensive and time-consuming
process or as

00:46:25.180 --> 00:46:26.309
economists say, they have lots of transaction
costs.

00:46:26.309 --> 00:46:30.421
And we've judiciously eliminated fair use
in a series of decisions in

00:46:30.421 --> 00:46:34.749
this country over the last ten years.
Many of the things that people sue about today,

00:46:34.749 --> 00:46:37.479
they wouldn't have to
sue about or they wouldn't sue about because

00:46:37.479 --> 00:46:42.130
effectively they should be
covered by this general free license of fair

00:46:42.130 --> 00:46:45.019
use.
If we put that back in the law, we would avoid

00:46:45.019 --> 00:46:46.809
a lot of the conflict
right away.

00:46:46.809 --> 00:46:50.380
And then thirdly, many of the features of
the DMCA, the Digital

00:46:50.380 --> 00:46:54.210
Millennium Copyright Act, passed in 2000,
particularly ones that make

00:46:54.210 --> 00:46:59.450
it, you know, illegal to reverse-engineer
DRM and some of the more

00:46:59.450 --> 00:47:03.130
draconian features of DMCA.
Take those out those.

00:47:03.130 --> 00:47:07.510
Three things I think would -- would kind of
be the Granger version of

00:47:07.510 --> 00:47:11.329
copy reform as opposed to what we've got now
which is the Russian

00:47:11.329 --> 00:47:16.470
Revolution of copyright reform.
And as I say, there's no -- there's no Theodore

00:47:16.470 --> 00:47:19.460
Roosevelt on the
horizon, that I know of, that's going to make

00:47:19.460 --> 00:47:22.960
that happen.
But, you know, if the conflict gets increasingly

00:47:22.960 --> 00:47:28.040
hostile, maybe
somebody will come up to do that.

