00:51:56.660 --> 00:52:01.029
&gt;&gt; So the first thing I noticed on this chart
was the thumbs down for

00:52:01.029 --> 00:52:10.270
network neutrality.
And many others may have noticed that as well.

00:52:10.270 --> 00:52:11.940
But could you elaborate a bit on that?

00:52:11.940 --> 00:52:14.069
LARRY DOWNES: Sure.
So I have about a half a chapter in the book

00:52:14.069 --> 00:52:17.420
where I talk about
infrastructure in particular but net neutrality.

00:52:17.420 --> 00:52:21.099
I should say I'm not opposed to net neutrality,
at least the principles

00:52:21.099 --> 00:52:24.980
of net neutrality.
My concern and it should be fairly obvious

00:52:24.980 --> 00:52:28.880
now why that would be, is
particularly with the idea that it would be

00:52:28.880 --> 00:52:32.883
both implemented and
enforced by the Federal Communications Commission.

00:52:32.883 --> 00:52:37.030
The idea again here that a terrestrial sort
of earth-bound governing

00:52:37.030 --> 00:52:41.380
body, in this case one is an extremely poor
track record for dealing

00:52:41.380 --> 00:52:45.029
with information.
You think about, you know, this day or at

00:52:45.029 --> 00:52:49.390
the FCC, because their
jurisdiction allows them to deal with content

00:52:49.390 --> 00:52:51.460
on the broadcast network,
only.

00:52:51.460 --> 00:52:56.589
They can't really enforce their views on the
cable network and on

00:52:56.589 --> 00:52:57.960
satellite.
But on broadcast they can.

00:52:57.960 --> 00:53:02.160
So you have literally the FCC trolling around,
looking for errant

00:53:02.160 --> 00:53:07.599
nipples and swear words.
And it's kind of sort of really nanny behavior

00:53:07.599 --> 00:53:10.619
that not only hasn't
been toned down, it's actually, you know,

00:53:10.619 --> 00:53:15.239
the number of enforcements
and the number of the size of the penalties

00:53:15.239 --> 00:53:18.150
has actually gone up.
You know, this is an agency where it's wearing

00:53:18.150 --> 00:53:22.559
it's content manager hat
that has not given us reason to believe that

00:53:22.559 --> 00:53:26.619
they get what 21st century
life is really about.

00:53:26.619 --> 00:53:31.309
So my concern is about it as a principally,
the FCC, sort of any

00:53:31.309 --> 00:53:35.849
traditional physical government, but particularly
the FCC is an awful

00:53:35.849 --> 00:53:40.950
place not only to divine the rules but then
my concern is particularly

00:53:40.950 --> 00:53:43.960
around enforcement.
If somebody says, okay so let's say the rules

00:53:43.960 --> 00:53:48.910
get passed, and under one
version of them any person in the world, any

00:53:48.910 --> 00:53:52.589
citizen of the United
States can file a complaint with the FCC if

00:53:52.589 --> 00:53:54.779
they think the rules are
being violated.

00:53:54.779 --> 00:53:58.479
The FCC must investigate within 180 days.
And let's say that's what goes into effect,

00:53:58.479 --> 00:54:03.719
so you can sort of imagine
the situation is, I'm at home, my cable seems

00:54:03.719 --> 00:54:05.619
really slow.
The Internet's really slow today.

00:54:05.619 --> 00:54:10.369
I bet, you know, that Comcast is messing with
the traffic.

00:54:10.369 --> 00:54:12.190
And I'm going to file a complaint with the
FCC and they're required to

00:54:12.190 --> 00:54:16.720
investigate it.
You know, and how are they going to investigate

00:54:16.720 --> 00:54:19.920
it?
Well, there's very little -- so they've been

00:54:19.920 --> 00:54:24.720
 -- there's sort of a lot
written about it that's from the lawyers standpoint.

00:54:24.720 --> 00:54:25.720
Sorry.
There's very little that's been written about

00:54:25.720 --> 00:54:29.309
it from the engineering
standpoint.

00:54:29.309 --> 00:54:34.019
What's the engineering behind how the FCC
would investigate and enforce

00:54:34.019 --> 00:54:37.019
the rules assuming that they're the ones charged
with that authority?

00:54:37.019 --> 00:54:42.479
Well, they're going to have -- it seems to
me that at least one likely

00:54:42.479 --> 00:54:45.950
way, and therefore the way that the FCC would
most prefer is that

00:54:45.950 --> 00:54:48.950
they're going to have to have access to the
traffic.

00:54:48.950 --> 00:54:51.150
Not necessarily, you know, looking at all
the packets, but they're

00:54:51.150 --> 00:54:53.680
going to have to say all right we're going
to do a compliance check or

00:54:53.680 --> 00:54:57.049
we're going to do and audit.
And we're going to look at what packets were

00:54:57.049 --> 00:54:59.940
moving at the time this
complaint takes place.

00:54:59.940 --> 00:55:03.989
And we're going to look to see if we see any
indication of non-neutral

00:55:03.989 --> 00:55:06.940
behavior.
Was it just the traffic was slow because the

00:55:06.940 --> 00:55:10.070
traffic was slow or was
the traffic was slow because the application

00:55:10.070 --> 00:55:11.339
I was using was Bit
Torrent or some other, you know, depreferred

00:55:11.339 --> 00:55:14.369
application.
Well, the only way they're really going to

00:55:14.369 --> 00:55:18.739
be able to determine that is
to look at least some of the traffic, put

00:55:18.739 --> 00:55:23.019
it back together, and the
minute the FCC is doing deep packet inspection

00:55:23.019 --> 00:55:26.289
is the minute that I
would expect the Civil Libertarians to get

00:55:26.289 --> 00:55:29.900
the most upset.
Because of course, they're looking at it for

00:55:29.900 --> 00:55:33.809
one purpose which is to
see if the wrong kind of stuff is being favored

00:55:33.809 --> 00:55:36.250
or disfavored.
But you know, this is the Federal Government.

00:55:36.250 --> 00:55:39.319
Now I'm not as paranoid as many of these groups
are, but you'd think

00:55:39.319 --> 00:55:41.999
that the more paranoid ones would be saying
that the minute that the

00:55:41.999 --> 00:55:44.959
FCC starts doing deep packet inspection what
they're going look for

00:55:44.959 --> 00:55:47.490
other interesting things they find and of
course the War on Terror,

00:55:47.490 --> 00:55:51.410
most of it done secretly.
They will turn over lots and lots of what

00:55:51.410 --> 00:55:56.599
they find as they look
inside -- you know, this is a worst case scenario.

00:55:56.599 --> 00:56:01.039
I don't necessarily think that makes it an
unlikely scenario and I

00:56:01.039 --> 00:56:04.660
worry about that tremendously.
So those sort of law of intended consequences

00:56:04.660 --> 00:56:09.630
with the rules and the
problems of enforcement are why I'm strongly

00:56:09.630 --> 00:56:15.039
opposed to the FCC having
the authority to make sure net neutrality

00:56:15.039 --> 00:56:17.729
 --
Net neutrality is fine.

00:56:17.729 --> 00:56:22.450
The FCC in charge of not so fine.
Yeah?

